                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">I accompanied a friend to Dragon Necropolis yesterday in order to help him get something that he needed from there.  Upon entering the zone, I noticed a small group of new humanoid NPCs by zone in.  A level 60 with us confirmed that at least one was an even con.
<br />

<br />
Feeling a little down from grouping in WoS earlier and doing the same old slow, tash, nuke nuke nuke thing, I was happy to be in a familiar expansion and proceeded to pull and charm one.  He had a max hit of 215 and judging from the rate of decline of his opponent's health (the same type of mob), I figured they had a fairly beefy HP pool for their dps.
<br />

<br />
All fine and dandy until I had to recharm and noticed that this 215 hitter was now slapping me around for 471.  So mobs on the new charm table aren't just limited to OOW zones.
<br />

<br />
Anyone interested in experiencing this first hand can find these particular mobs right at the DN zone in, a small pack of 3.  They're called "A mercenary excavator".
<br />

<br />
  I have been programming computers for just about 20 years now, so I have a theory of whats going on here.  I believe they added a new database field for every mob in the game that provides a scalar coefficient for some damage modification formula.  When introduced (for all pre-oow mobs), this field was initialized with a value that left the mob's charmed dps unchanged.  I believe that this field defaults (for all new mobs) to some value that gives us the vastly reduced dps that we're all too familiar with from OOW.  I believe this is the case, because I can see no other reason to reduce the dps from these particular mobs in DN (although I could be wrong on this point).
<br />

<br />
The implications of this are exceedingly bothersome.  If my theory is correct, then ANY mob added into the game from now on, no matter where in the game they are added, will be practically useless to charm.
<br />

<br />
I hope I'm wrong.
<br />

<br />
Raeaan</span><span class="postbody"></span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
                        </tr>
                </table></td>
        </tr>
